@node Config "Configuration"
@{fg highlight}Configuration
-------------@{fg text}

Configuration is supported through use of Workbench ToolTypes or CLI
parameters. If any options are not included, the stated defaults will be
used.

Configuration options are not case sensitive.

Invalid options will be ignored. In this case, the default values will
be used.


The following configuration commands are supported:

  @{b}Definition@{ub}
    Description: Compiles the given definition upon startup. No file
                 requester is presented unless the module can not be found.

                 The definition name is referenced as the path and filename
                 within the 'definitions' directory.

    Default: NONE : FileRequester

    Example: Definition=Roland/Juno-106.def

  @{b}ErrorLog@{ub}
    Description: Outputs error messages to the given file rather using
                 requesters. This option is recommed for batch file
                 processing.

    Default: Requesters

    Example: ErrorLog=RAM:MSE-Compiler.errors


  @{b}Font@{ub}
    Description: Sets an 8 point font for the window text. This should
    be a non-proportioanl font.

    Default: Topaz2.font

    Example: Font=Courier.font


  @{b}Last@{ub}
    Description: Compiles the last compiled definition. No file
                 requester is presented unless the last used definition
                 file can not be found.

    Valid values: Last

    Default: NO

    Example: Last


  @{b}WindowL@{ub}
    Description: Sets the position of the left edge of the window.

    Valid values: >= 0

    Default: 0

    Example: WindowL=50


  @{b}WindowT@{ub}
    Description: Sets the position of the top edge of the window.

    Valid values: >= 0

    Default: 0

    Example: WindowT=100
@endnode
@node Overview "Language Overview"
@{fg highlight}Language Overview
-----------------@{fg text}

All commands, parameters, options, values, etc. must be separated by a
SPACE (032), LF-line feed (010), or TAB (007) character. LF-line feed +
CR-carriage return (010+013), such as used on DOS systems, is supported.

A command structure is a group of parameters applicable to a command.
Command structures must be enclosed within brackets (). The end of
structure indicator ')', must always be followed by a LF character (or
LF+CR).

Except for TAB (007), ASCII characters from (000) to (031) are not
permitted.

All commands, parameters and options are case sensitive. Therefore,
'Define Device' is accepted, but 'DEFine DeViCe' is not.

The Module Compiler has the capability of determining the height of a
gadget based on the height of the requested font. In some cases, the
width is automatically determined as well. This seems to work well with
most fonts. Optional parameters may be added in a future version, if
there are problems with the internal determinations.

In most cases, it is permissable to order commands and parameters in any
manner wished. But, there are some restrictions, as noted in the
reference section. Regardless of the semi-freeform capability, it is
suggested that the recommended ordering and format be used.
@endnode
@node Format "Format"
@{fg highlight}Format
------@{fg text}

There are several ways to format a definition (.def) file, but for
consistency, one is recommended. For example, the 'Define Font'
parameter, 'Style' could be formatted as:

The recommended format:

     Style (
       UNDERLINED
       BOLD
     )

is equivalent to (sometimes preferred):

     Style ( UNDERLINED BOLD )

and, is equivalent to:

     Style
     (
     UNDERLINED
     BOLD
     )

or even this format will work, but is not recommended:

     Style
       (        UNDERLINED
 BOLD
           )
@endnode
@node Conventions "Conventions"
@{fg highlight}Conventions
-----------@{fg text}

@{b}bold@{ub} Denotes required
plain denotes optional
@{b}@{i}bold+italic@{ui}@{ub} denotes optional-required.

[...] Denotes

<> Denotes required items. The '<' and '>' characters should not be
   included.

[] Denotes optional items. The '[' and ']' characters should not be
   included.

{} Denotes optional-required items. Only one of these options may be used
   within a structure but one of them is required. The '{' and '}'
   characters should not be included.

|  Denotes OR. Only one of these options may be used with this item.
   The '|' character should not be included.


<#>  Denotes an integer numeric value in decimal format (BASE 10). The
     range is determined by the parameter it is used with.

     Examples: 10,   9,   5,   127


<$#> Denotes an integer numeric value in hexadecimal format (BASE 16).
     The value can be written in any of the following forms:

               $#     #$     h#     #h     H#     #H

     Examples: $AE,   AE$,   hAE,   AEh,   HAE,   AEH

<%#> Denotes an integer numeric value in binary format (BASE 2). The
     value can be written in any of the following forms:

               %#     #%     b#     #b     B#     #B

     Examples: %0010, 0010%, b0010, 0010b, B0010, 0010B

<A> Denotes an integer numeric value in numeric character format:

               #<char>

     Examples: #A,   #B,   #5,   #@,   #y

<#$A> Some parameters allow values to be defined in several formats.
      Denotes an integer numeric value in decimal, hexadecimal or numeric
      character format.

<asc> Denotes an integer numeric value (BASE 10) in the range of 0-255.
      This is used to reference characters within the ASCII character
      set. Values not included within a charcter set are not permitted.

<bitpattern>   '--aa-a' is equivalent to 'aa-a'

<bitstring>    '--aaa--bb' is equivalent to 'aaa--bb'

<float> Denotes a floating point value in decimal format (BASE 10).

     Examples: 0.54,   103.2,   20.5

<left>   Denote integer numeric values (BASE 10) in pixels, in the range
<top>    of 0 to n, where n is the maximum width of the screen/window.
<width>  Currently, the default screen is 640 x 400.
<height>

<midi> Denotes an integer numeric value (BASE 10) in the range of 0-127.
       This data is sent within the MIDI data stream.

<name> Denotes text information enclosed within quotation marks. For
       compatibility with ARexx support, spaces are not permitted.

       NOTE: <name>s are, currently, only used by the Module Compiler for
       reference, and are not stored in the output module. However, a
       future release will support ARexx and these <name>s will be used.
       For this reason, it is recommended that <name>s be used that
       reflect the actual use.

<offset> Denotes an integer numeric value (BASE 10) beginning count from 0.

<offsetstring> Denotes a string of offsets. Each of 'a', 'b', etc. is an
               integer numeric value (BASE 10) beginning count from 0.

    Examples: "a0b3", "a0b1c2d5"

<string> Denotes any text information enclosed within quotation marks.

<type> Denotes a type reference, as supported by the command it is used
       with. Only one type may be selected from those supported.
@endnode
@node RootCommandOrder "Root Command Order"
@{fg highlight}Root Command Order
------------------@{fg text}

    @{b}Define Device@{ub} ()
    Define Usage ()

    Define Palette ()
    @{b}Define Font@{ub} <name> ()

    Set Font <name> ]
    Set Color <#> ]

    @{b}Define Window@{ub} <name> ()
    Define Midi <name> ()
    Define Initialize ()
    Define Link <name> ()

    @{b}Window@{ub} <name> ()
@endnode
