@node Com_' "' Comment"
@{fg highlight}'                          ' Comment                             OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: The comment marker (apostrophe) can appear anywhere within a
definition file. All text after the comment marker, on the same line, is
ignored.

Comments can be very handy as reminders of how or why you did something a
certain way. Also, the comment marker can be very useful when debugging a
definition file, by providing a method of temporarly ignoring commands or
parameters, without having to delete the text.
@endnode
@node Com_DefineData "Define Data"
@{fg highlight}Define Data                                                      OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Define Data <name> (
    @{b}Type@{ub} Cycle_MX|List
    @{b}Data@{ub} (
      <string>
      ...
    )
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE
Placement: before Window

Description: This command is used to define shared data for use with
gadget type definitions.

PARAMETERS

@{b}Data@{ub}                                                             REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This structure is used to define the data. There must be at least two
strings within the data structure.

Placement: after Type

      Example:
                              Data (
                                "Sawtooth"
                                "Pulse"
                                "Triangle"
                                "Square"
                              )



@{b}Type@{ub}                                                             REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Defines the gadget type that the data will be shared with. Cycle_MX
type, can be shared with both Cycle and MX gadgets. Other types may only be
shared for use with that gadget type.

Placement: before Data
@endnode
@node Com_DefineDevice "Define Device"
@{fg highlight}@{b}Define Device@{ub}                                                     REQUIRED
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  @{b}Define Device@{ub} (
    @{b}Manufacturer@{ub} <string>
    @{b}Device@{ub} <string>
    Part <string>
    Channel <#>
    CharSet (
      @{b}@{i}az2AZ
      Disable@{ui}@{ub} (
        <#$%A> | <#$%A>-<#$%A>
        [...]
      )
      @{b}@{i}Remap@{ui}@{ub} (
        <#$%A> [to] <#$%A>
        [...]
      )
    )
    Checksum [<preprocess>] <method>
    Handler <handler>
    MaxChannel <#>
    NoteRange <low> <high>
    Updates Final
  )


Occurance: SINGLE
Placement: FIRST

Description: This command is used to define standard MIDI SYSEX, formats
and communication information for a device.

@{b}Device@{ub}                                                           REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
<string>

  Defines the name of the device.

@{b}Manufacturer@{ub}                                                     REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
<string>

  Defines the manufacturer of the device. All modules (.mse) files with
  a common Manufacturer will be organized together in a directory with
  that name.

Part                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
<string>

  For definitions with multiple parts, this defines the name of the part.


Channel                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
<#>

  Sets the midi channel. Value must be within the range 1 to MaxChannel.
  This value is offset by +1 from the actual MIDI channel which ranges
  from 0 to 15. This value will be adjusted automatically by
  MSE-Compiler. See MaxChannel for more information.

  Default: 1

CharSet                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Defines a character set for STRING type gadgets and provides a method of
re-mapping ASCII characters to their proper MIDI values.

Some device fonts do not follow the ASCII standard by including custom
characters and/or re-ordering the characters. By defining the character
set, compatibility with system fonts can be achieved.

az2AZ

  Converts lowercase characters (a-z) to uppercase (A-Z). This is
  different than remapping because the visual display is also changed.
  Remapped characters appear the same as typed, they just get different
  numerical representations.

Disable ()

  Defines ASCII characters that are not allowed within the character set
  of the device.

  Example:

      Disable (
        #! #@-#) #0
      )

   Result: Disables the '!', characters '@' to ')', and 0-9.

  Default: All ASCII characters 31-126 are allowed.

Remap ()

  Remaps ASCII characters to different values.

  Example:

      Remap (
        #A to $15
        $20 to 5
      )

   Result: Remaps A-Z (normally ASCII 65-90) to 21-46, and the 'space'
           (normally ASCII 32) to 5.

  Default: Characters are mapped to standard ASCII.

For Disable and Remap there are three special case definitions: 'A', 'a'
and '0'. These definitions also affect other characters. For example,
#A would also affect the letters B-Z. Definitions, such as #B, for these
included letters are not allowed.

         #A | 65 | $41     affects A-Z
         #a | 97 | $61     affects a-z
         #0 | 48 | $30     affects 0-9

Checksum                                                         OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
<preprocess>

  NybbleLM

    Calculates the byte value for determining the checksum by first
    reconstructing values stored in 2 byte NybbleLM format. (See 'Midi'
    for more information about NybbleLM format).

  NybbleML

    Calculates the byte value for determining the checksum by first
    reconstructing values stored in 2 byte NybbleML format. (See 'Midi'
    for more information about NybbleML format).

  Default: NONE

<method>

  2sComp

    Bytes are summed in seven bits ignoring overflows and the result is
    the 2s Complement of that sum (checksum = ((not(sum))+1) and $7F).

  Sum

    Bytes are summed in seven bits ignoring overflows and the result is
    the checksum (checksum = sum).

  Zero

    Bytes are summed in seven bits ignoring overflows. The checksum is
    calculated such that the sum + checksum is 0 (checksum = $80 - sum).

  Default: NONE

Handler                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Defines the handler to use for midi messages.

<handler>

  BlueRibbon

    Uses the BlueRibbon.library to handle midi messages. Allows
    MIDI SYStem EXplorer to share the midi port with other programs that
    use this library (ex: Bars & Pipes).

  TPP1 | TPP2 | TPP3

    Uses the BlueRibbon.library in conjunction with the Triple Play Plus
    hardware to handle outgoing midi messages. Allows MIDI SYStem
    EXplorer to share the midi ports with other programs that use this
    library (ex: Bars & Pipes). Use TPP# to designate which of the midi
    outputs to use.

  CAMD

    Uses the camd.library to handle midi messages. Allows MIDI SYStem
    EXplorer to share the midi port with other programs that use this
    library (ex: Deluxe Music).

  MIDI

    Uses the MIDI.library to handle midi messages. Allows
    MIDI SYStem EXplorer to share the midi port with other programs that
    use this library.

  File

    Routes all outgoing midi messages to a file. This can be used for
    debugging when developing new modules.

  Default: NONE

MaxChannel                                                       OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
<#>

  Sets the maximum midi channel. Value must be within the range 1 to 32.
  This value is offset by +1 from the actual MIDI channel which ranges
  from 0 to 31. This value will be adjusted automatically by
  MSE-Compiler.

  Default: 16

NoteRange                                                        OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------



Updates                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Final

  Forces all gadgets in this module to only send MIDI messages for the
  final gadget value. Some MIDI devices can not handle continuous
  streams of MIDI data. Slider gadgets, especially, can generate 1000s
  of bytes of data while the slider value is being adjusted. Some older
  MIDI devices may lock up or ignore some updates if this is not set. If
  a module seems to stop working during heavy editing this may solve the
  problem.

  Default: Continuous
@endnode
@node Com_DefineFont "Define Font"
@{fg highlight}@{b}Define Font@{ub}                                                      REQUIRED
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  @{b}Define Font@{ub} <name> (
    @{b}Name@{ub} <string>
    Size <#>
    Style ( [BOLD] [ITALIC] [UNDERLINED] )
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE
Placement: before Window

Description: This command is used to open Amiga fonts for use with other
commands having text based parameters. The defined font becomes the
GLOBAL DEFAULT from this point on. At least one Define Font must be used.

PARAMETERS

@{b}Name@{ub}                                                             REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
<string>

  This is the filename of a font contained within the FONTS: directory.
  The full name should be used.

  Example: Name "Topaz2p.font"

Size                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
<#>

  This sets the pointsize, in pixels, to be used with the font. If this
  pointsize is not found, it will be created by scaling another size.
  Generally, scaled fonts look really bad. Therefore, it is recommended
  that existing font sizes be used.

  Default: 8

Style                                                            OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
BOLD
ITALIC
UNDERLINED

  This is used to apply style(s) to a font. BOLD, ITALIC and UNDERLINED
  can be used in any combination. These styles are only applied to text
  displayed using the Text command. Other commands, such as Gadget, will
  ignore style definitions. At least one style must be set for this
  parameter.

  Examples: Style ( BOLD ITALIC )
            Style ( UNDERLINED )

  Default: Plain

@endnode
@node Com_DefineInitialize "Define Intialize"
@{fg highlight}Define Initialize                                                OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Define Initialize (
    @{b}Midi@{ub} (
    )
  )


Occurance: SINGLE
Placement: after Define Midi

Description: When a module is first opened it attempts an initialization
procedure to set up the MIDI device for use with the module. Generally,
the initialization procedure will be used to select a patch on the device
for editing.

This command is used to define MIDI messages that will be used to
initialize the device.
@endnode
@node Com_DefineLink "Define Link"
@{fg highlight}Define Link                                                      OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Define Link <name> (
    @{b}Type@{ub} <type> ()
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE
Placement: before Window

Description: This command is used to define links for use with other
definitions, as a way of supporting additional information/functions.

Some MIDI devices have displays that combine graphical representations
with numerical/text information. This command provides a method of
including this information through graphics and/or external functions.

This command also provides a method of managing multiple windows.

See Link Type descriptions for more information.
@endnode
@node Com_DefineMidi "Define Midi"
@{fg highlight}Define Midi                                                      OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Define Midi <name> (
    Loadable
    Checksum (
      @{b}Offset@{ub} <offset>
      @{b}Range@{ub} <start> <end>
    )
    @{b}@{i}Data@{ui}@{ub} (
      <#$%>
      <string>
      Byte
      Bytes <#>
      Nybble
      Nybbles <#>
    ) }
    @{b}@{i}DataFile@{ui}@{ub} <string> }
    Midi (
    )
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE
Placement: before Window

Description: This command is used to define MIDI messages for
communication with a MIDI device. These definitions can be used by
gadgets to directly control the device. Multiple definitions can be used
to provide different kinds of control (Patch, Parameter, etc.). MIDI
definitions can be transmitted as is, or data can be inserted by a Gadget
Midi parameter. This provides a method of inter-connection, allowing
gadget values to modify MIDI definitions.

Midi and Define Midi are easily confused.  Define Midi defines an
unchanging structure for a MIDI message. While, the Midi command defines
information that changes, based on the values of the gadget it is defined
within and/or other gadgets. Midi definitions are automatically updated
and inserted into a Define Midi structure, whenever the value of a
referenced gadget changes.

PARAMETERS

Loadable                                                         OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Allows this Define Midi to be saved or loaded.  present, this activates
MSE's patch loading and saving ability.

Only one Define Midi can be made Loadable within a definition.
@endnode
@node Com_DefinePalette "Define Palette"
@{fg highlight}Define Palette                                                   OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Define Palette (
    <#> <r> <g> <b>
    [...]
  )

Occurance: SINGLE
Placement: before Window

Description: This command is used to modify colors within the palette.
Colors 0-3 are used for gadget and window rendering and can not be modified.


PARAMETERS

<#>

  Selects the color # within the palette. Range 4-31.

<r>

  Sets the RED component level from 0-15.

<g>

  Sets the GREEN component level from 0-15.

<b>

  Sets the BLUE component level from 0-15.

@endnode
@node Com_DefineWindow "Define Window"
@{fg highlight}@{b}Define Window@{ub}                                                    REQUIRED
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  @{b}Define Window@{ub} <name> (
    @{b}Position@{ub} <left> <top>
    @{b}@{i}Position2@{ui}@{ub} <right> <bottom>
    @{b}@{i}Size@{ui}@{ub} <width> <height>
    Font <name>
    Color <#>
    Border
    DragBar
    Title
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE
Placement: before Window

Description: This command is used to define a window to which gadgets,
text, etc. can be attached. Multiple windows can be defined for
applications where one window is not enough to include all MIDI parameters
required. Using the Link Window command, windows can be grouped together
so that only one window in a group is displayed at a time. For this
reason, it is permissable for windows to overlap each other. The Show
Window command can be used to set the front window at startup.

PARAMETERS

@{b}Position@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------

This sets the co-ordinates, in pixels, of the upper left hand corner
of the window. The values for <left> and <top> must be within the range
of the screen.

To avoid overlapping the screen's titlebar, it is suggested that a minimum
value of 11 be used for <top> when using an 8 point screen font.

@{b}@{i}Size
Position2@{ui}@{ub}                                               OPTIONAL REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
'Size' sets the dimensions of the window, in pixels. The values of
<width> + <left> and <height> + <top> must be within the range of
the screen. This is an alternative to 'Position2'. Use one or the other,
but not both.

'Position2' sets the co-ordinates, in pixels, of the lower right hand
corner of the window. The values for <right> and <bottom> must
be within the range of the screen (640 x 400) and greater than
the <left> and <top> values of 'Position'. This is an
alternative to 'Size'. Use one or the other, but not both.


Font                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------

This sets the default font for this window. Unless otherwise
specified by the Font parameter within a Window command, this
font will override the GLOBAL DEFAULT within any Window command
that references this defined window.

If not included, the GLOBAL DEFAULT will be used.

Color                                                            OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the default color for this window. Unless otherwise
specified by the Color parameter within a Window command, this
color will override the GLOBAL DEFAULT within any Window command
that references this defined window.

If not included, the GLOBAL DEFAULT will be used.

Border                                                           OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This gives the window standard intuition borders.

DragBar                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This gives the window an intuition dragbar and allows it to be moved.
This options forces the Border option to be in effect.

Title                                                            OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This gives the window the title <name>. This options forces the DragBar
option to be in effect and allows the window to be moved.
@endnode
@node Com_SetColor "Set Color"
@{fg highlight}Set Color                                                        OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Set Color <#>


Occurance: SINGLE
Placement: before Define Window

Description: This command is used to define the GLOBAL DEFAULT color for
commands not including an optional Color parameter. If not included, an
internal default will be used.
@endnode
@node Com_SetFont "Set Font"
@{fg highlight}Set Font                                                         OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Set Font <name>


Occurance: SINGLE
Placement: before Define Window

Description: This command is used to define the GLOBAL DEFAULT font for
commands not including an optional Font parameter. If not included, an
internal default will be used.
@endnode
@node Com_Window "Window"
@{fg highlight}@{b}Window@{ub}                                                           REQUIRED
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  @{b}Window@{ub} <name> (
    Gadget <name> ()
    Image <string> ()
    Text <string> ()
    Border ()
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE
Placement: after Define Window / after Define Midi / after Define Link

Description: This command is used to attach Gadget, Image, Text and
Border definitions to a previously defined window.

PARAMETERS

See PARAMETER COMMANDS.
@endnode
@node ParCom_Border "Border"
@{fg highlight}Border                                                           OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  @{b}Border@{ub} (
    @{b}Position@{ub} <left> <top>
    @{b}@{i}Position2@{ui}@{ub} <right> <bottom>
    @{b}@{i}Size@{ui}@{ub} <width> <height>
    Fill <#>
    Frame 3D|3D-Recess|NONE
  )

Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: This command is used to define a border to be drawn in a
window.

A border can be used as a method of visually grouping gadgets together, or
just to spice up the look of the display.

PARAMETERS

@{b}Position@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the co-ordinates, in pixels, of the upper left hand
corner of the border. The values for <left> and <top> must be
within the range of the referenced window.

@{b}@{i}Size
Position2@{ui}@{ub}                                               OPTIONAL REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
'Size' sets the dimensions of the border, in pixels. The values of
<width> + <left> and <height> + <top> must be within the range of
the referenced window. This is an
alternative to 'Position2'. Use one or the other, but not both.

'Position2' sets the co-ordinates, in pixels, of the lower right hand
corner of the border. The values for <right> and <bottom> must
be within the range of the referenced window. and greater than
the <left> and <top> values of 'Position'. This is an
alternative to 'Size'. Use one or the other, but not both.

Fill                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This is used to apply a fill color to a border. A value of 0, the
default background color, will have no visual effect.

NOTE: Some gadgets do not render properly when displayed over a
non-background (0) color. For this reason, fill may not always
produce expected or pleasing results.

If not included, no fill will be applied to the border.

Frame                                                            OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This is used to set the visual rendering of the border's edges.
@endnode
@node ParCom_Gadget "Gadget"
@{fg highlight}Gadget                                                           OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  @{b}Gadget@{ub} <name> (
    @{b}Position@{ub} <left> <top>
    Font <name>
    @{b}Type@{ub} <type> ()
    Midi <name> ()
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: This command is used to define a gadget and its placement in
a window.

PARAMETERS

@{b}Position@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the co-ordinates, in pixels, of the upper left hand
corner of the gadget. The values for <left> and <top> must be
within the range of the referenced window.

Font                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the font to be used when rendering the current gadget.
This value overrides the Window's Default and the GLOBAL DEFAULT.

Style definitions, within the referenced font definition, are ignored.

If not included, the Window's Default (if defined) or the GLOBAL
DEFAULT will be used.

Placement: before Type

@{b}Type@{ub}                                                             REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the type of Gadget being defined. Type parameters are included
within this structure. See Gadget Types.

Placement: before Midi, after Font

Midi                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Placement: after Type

@endnode
@node ParCom_Image "Image"
@{fg highlight}Image                                                            OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Image <string> (
    @{b}Position@{ub} <left> <top>
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: This command is used to display an image within a window.

@{b}<string>@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Defines the file name. This must include the full path.

@{b}Position@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the co-ordinates, in pixels, of the image. The values for
<left> and <top> must be within the range of the referenced window.
@endnode
@node ParCom_Midi "Midi"
@{fg highlight}Midi                                                             OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Midi <name> (
    @{b}Data@{ub} (
      <offset> <value> [<modifier>] <method> <...>
    [ ... ]
    )
    Send
  )

Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: This command is used to insert data into a MIDI message
defined with the Define Midi command. Data is inserted, by offset, into
a Define Midi definition.

Midi and Define Midi are easily confused.  Define Midi defines an
unchanging structure for a MIDI message. While, the Midi command defines
information that changes, based on the values of the gadget it is defined
within or variables. Midi definitions are automatically updated and
re-inserted into a Define Midi structure, whenever the value of a gadget
changes.


<offset>

  Offset, counting from 0, to store <value> within the 'Define Midi'
  message.


<value>

  <#$%>
  <string>

  CHANNEL

    Uses the current Midi Channel as <value>. This value is always
    stored in the lower four bits (0-3) of the destination byte, leaving
    the upper four bits (4-7) intact.

  VALUE

    Uses the value of the gadget as <value>. Or in the case of a STRING
    type gadget, uses each individual character as <value>, performing
    this function for each character in the gadget.


<modifier>

  Magnitude <bit#>

    Modifies a negative <value> using 8-bit 'Sign Magnitude' encoding
    (magnitude bit is set to %1 for negative or %0 for positive values).
    Values >= 0 are unchanged. <bit#> defines the bit used to hold the
    magnitude bit).

    Example:  10 (%00001010)
     Modify: Magnitude 4
     Result: $0A (%00001010)  No change to value >= 0

    Example: -10 (%00001010)
     Modify: Magnitude 4
     Result: $1A (%00011010)

    Example: -10 (%00001010)
     Modify: Magnitude 6
     Result: $4A (%01001010)


  Offset <#>

    Modifies <value> using 'Offset Binary' encoding (adds an offset).

    Example: -10
     Modify: Offset 12
     Result: 2 (%00000010)

    Example: 125
     Modify: Offset -24
     Result: 101 (%01100101)


  Signed

    Modifies a negative <value> using 8-bit 'Twos Complement' encoding
    (take absolute value, flip all bits and add 1 to that value).
    Values >= 0 are unchanged.

    Example:  10 (%00001010)
     Result: $0A (%00001010)  No change to value >= 0

    Example: -10
    Process:  10  %00001010   absolute value
                  ---------
                  %11110101   flip all bits
                + %00000001   add 1
                  ---------
     Result: $F6 (%11110110)

             Note that $F6 would be invalid for a midi sysex message and
             must be stored, using <method>, as a 7-bit value or as
             multiple bytes.


<method>

  Bit <0-7>

    Stores <value> (0|1) into the specified bit of the destination byte.
    Leaves other bits intact. Useful for devices that store more than one
    parameter within a single byte.

    Example: 15 1 Bit 4
     Result: before: $AE (%10101110) in byte 15
              after: $BE (%10111110) in byte 15

  Bits <0-7>-<0-7>

    Stores <value> into the specified bit range of the destination byte.
    Leaves other bits intact. Useful for devices that store more than one
    parameter within a single byte.

    Example: 15 %1111 Bits 3-6
     Result: before: $00 (%00000000) in byte 15
              after: $78 (%01111000) in byte 15

    Example: 15 %1100 Bits 3-6
     Result: before: $AE (%10101110) in byte 15
              after: $E6 (%11100110) in byte 15

  BitsA <bitpattern>

    Stores <value> into the specified bit pattern of the destination
    byte. Leaves other bits intact. Useful for devices that store more
    than one parameter within a single byte. <bitpattern> is right
    justified within the byte. 8-bit or 16-bit patterns can be used.

    Example: 15 %1111 BitsA --a-aa-a
     Result: before: $00  (%00000000) in byte 15
              after: $2D  (%00101101) in byte 15

    Example: 15 %1100 BitsA --a-aa-a
     Result: before: $AE  (%10101110) in byte 15
              after: $AA  (%10101010) in byte 15

    Example: 15 %1111 BitsA ------aaa-a-----
    Process: before:      (%0000000000000000)
              after:      (%0000001110100000)
     Result: $03 (%00000011) in byte 15
             $A0 (%10100000) in byte 16

  Byte

    Stores <value> into the destination byte without any change.

  NybbleLM

    Stores <value> in 2 byte nybble format with bits 0-3 in destination byte
    and bits 4-7 in destination byte + 1.	 Bits 4-7 of both bytes will be
    set to 0. <offset> should reference byte 1. LM refers to least
    significant bits (LSB) and most significant bits (MSB).

    This is equivalent to doing the following:
      <offset> VALUE XBits bbbbaaaa

    Example: 15 $5D NybbleLM
     Result: stores $D (%00001101) in byte 15
             stores $5 (%00000101) in byte 16

  NybbleML

    Stores <value> in 2 byte nybble format with bits 4-7 in destination byte
    and bits 0-3 in destination byte + 1.	 Bits 4-7 of both bytes will be
    set to 0. <offset> should reference byte 1. ML refers to most
    significant bits (MSB) and least significant bits (LSB).

    This is equivalent to doing the following:
      <offset> VALUE XBits aaaabbbb

    Example: 15 $5D NybbleML
     Result: stores $5 (%00000101) in byte 15
             stores $D (%00001101) in byte 16

  XBits <bitstring>

    Extracts the specified bits from <value> and stores them in the lower
    bits of the destination byte.

    Example: 15 %01011101 XBits aaaabbbb
     Result:  5 (%0101) in byte 15
             13 (%1101) in byte 16

    Example: 15 %01011101 XBits bba
     Result:  1 (% 1) in byte 15
              2 (%10) in byte 16

    Example: 15 %01011101 XBits aacefdb-
     Result:  1 (%01) in byte 15
              0 (% 0) in byte 16
              0 (% 0) in byte 17
              1 (% 1) in byte 18
              1 (% 1) in byte 19
              1 (% 1) in byte 20

    Example: 15 %01011101 XBits -----aa-
     Result:  2 (%10) in byte 15

  XBitsOffset <bitstring> <offsetstring>

    Extracts the specified bits from <value> and stores them in the lower
    bits of the destination byte. Allows <offsetstring> for split value
    storage.

    Example: 15 %01011101 XBits aacefdb- a0,b1,c5,d6,e7,f10
     Result:  1 (%01) in byte 15 (a0  : 15+0)
              0 (% 0) in byte 16 (b1  : 15+1)
              0 (% 0) in byte 20 (c5  : 15+5)
              1 (% 1) in byte 21 (d6  : 15+6)
              1 (% 1) in byte 22 (e7  : 15+7)
              1 (% 1) in byte 25 (f10 : 15+10)
@endnode
@node ParCom_Text "Text"
@{fg highlight}Text                                                             OPTIONAL
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Text <string>|MANUFACTURER|DEVICE (
    @{b}Position@{ub} <left> <baseline>
    Font <name>
    Color <#>
    Shadow
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: This command is used to display text within a window.

MANUFACTURER
DEVICE
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
The options MANUFACTURER and DEVICE may be used instead of <string> to
use names as defined in 'Define Device'.

@{b}Position@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the co-ordinates, in pixels, of the text. The values for
<left> and <baseline> must be within the range of the referenced window.

Font                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the font to be used when rendering this text. This value
overrides the Window's Default and the GLOBAL DEFAULT.

Style definitions, within the referenced font definition, are
supported.

If not included, the Window's Default (if defined) or the GLOBAL
DEFAULT will be used.

Color                                                            OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the color to be used when rendering this text. This
value overrides the Window's Default and the GLOBAL DEFAULT.

If not included, the Window's Default (if defined) or the GLOBAL
DEFAULT will be used.

Shadow                                                           OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Applies a shadow in color 1 (Black) offset 2 pixels to the right
and 1 pixel down from the coordinates defined with 'Position'.
@endnode
@node Gad_Button "Type Button"
@{fg highlight}Type Button
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type Button (
    @{b}Label@{ub} <string>
    @{b}Link@{ub} <name>
    @{b}Size@{ub} <width> <height>
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: BUTTON gadgets are used to execute internal macros or
external scripts.

PARAMETERS

@{b}Label@{ub}                                                            REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the text that appears on the button gadget.

@{b}Link@{ub}                                                             REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Only 'ARexx' type links with one data may be used with 'Button' type gadgets.

@{b}Size@{ub}                                                             REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the dimensions of the gadget, in pixels. The value of
<width> and <height> must be within the range of the referenced
window.
@endnode
@node Gad_Cycle "Type Cycle"
@{fg highlight}Type Cycle
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type Cycle (
    @{b}@{i}Data@{ui}@{ub} <name>
    @{b}@{i}Data@{ui}@{ub} (
      <string>
      ...
    )
    DataValues ()
    Default <#>
    Link <name>
    Width <#>
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: CYCLE gadgets are used when a set number of options are
allowed (such as ON/OFF, PULSE/SAWTOOTH/TRIANGLE/etc.)

PARAMETERS

@{b}@{i}Data@{ui}@{ub}                                                    OPTIONAL REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This structure is used to define possible options for the gadget. There
must be at least two strings within the data structure.

      Example:
                              Data (
                                "Sawtooth"
                                "Pulse"
                                "Triangle"
                                "Square"
                              )

Optionally, a data structure previously defined with 'Define Data' may be
referenced.

      Example:
                              Data "Cycle1"



DataValues                                                       OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This structure is used to define the values for each of the options
included in the 'Data' stucture. If not included, the position within
the list (counting from 0) will be used.

      Example:                DataValues (
                                5 10 15 20
                              )

Default                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This defines the default state of the gadget. The range of possible
values is 0 to n, where n is the number of data.

      Example: To set the default to "Triangle", in the above example,
          use:
                              Default 2

      Default: 0
    Placement: after Data

Link                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Not valid with calculated type links, such as 'Note' or 'Numbers'.

    Placement: after Data


Width                                                            OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Width in characters.

      Default: wide enough for the longest string in the 'Data' structure.
@endnode
@node Gad_List "Type List"
@{fg highlight}Type List
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type List (
    @{b}Size@{ub} <width> <height>
    @{b}@{i}Data@{ui}@{ub} <name>
    @{b}@{i}Data@{ui}@{ub} (
      <string>
      ...
    )
    DataValues ()
    Default <#>
    Link <name>
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: LIST gadgets are used when a set number of options are
allowed (such as ON/OFF, PULSE/SAWTOOTH/TRIANGLE/etc.). It is similar in
use to CYCLE gadgets but preferred when there are many options.


PARAMETERS

@{b}@{i}Data@{ui}@{ub}                                                    OPTIONAL REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This structure is used to define possible options for the gadget. There
must be at least two strings within the data structure.

      Example:
                              Data (
                                "Sawtooth"
                                "Pulse"
                                "Triangle"
                                "Square"
                              )

Optionally, a data structure previously defined with 'Define Data' may be
referenced.

      Example:
                              Data "List1"


DataValues                                                       OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This structure is used to define the values for each of the options
included in the 'Data' stucture. If not included, the position within
the list (counting from 0) will be used.

      Example:                DataValues (
                                5 10 15 20
                              )

Default                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This defines the default state of the gadget. The range of possible
values is 0 to n, where n is the number of data.

      Example: To set the default to "Triangle", in the above example,
          use:
                              Default 2

      Default: 0
    Placement: after Data

Link                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Not valid with calculated type links, such as 'Note' or 'Numbers'.

    Placement: after Data


@{b}Size@{ub}                                                             REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the dimensions of the gadget, in pixels. The value of
<width> and <height> must be within the range of the referenced
window.
@endnode
@node Gad_MX "Type MX"
@{fg highlight}Type MX
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type MX (
    @{b}@{i}Data@{ui}@{ub} <name>
    @{b}@{i}Data@{ui}@{ub} (
      <string>
      ...
    )
    DataValues ()
    Default <#>
    LabelPlace LEFT|RIGHT
    Link <name>
    Spacing <#>
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: MX (Mutually Exclusive) gadgets are used when a set number
of options are allowed (such as ON/OFF, PULSE/SAWTOOTH/TRIANGLE/etc.).
They operate similar to 'Cycle'gadgets, but display all possible options
at once.

PARAMETERS

@{b}@{i}Data@{ui}@{ub}                                                    OPTIONAL REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This structure is used to define possible options for the gadget. There
must be at least two strings within the data structure.

      Example:
                              Data (
                                "Sawtooth"
                                "Pulse"
                                "Triangle"
                                "Square"
                              )

Optionally, a data structure previously defined with 'Define Data' may be
referenced.

      Example:
                              Data "MX1"


DataValues                                                       OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This structure is used to define the values for each of the options
included in the 'Data' stucture. If not included, the position within
the list (counting from 0) will be used.

      Example:                DataValues (
                                5 10 15 20
                              )



Default                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This defines the default state of the gadget. The range of possible
values is 0 to n, where n is the number of strings.

      Example: To set the default to "Triangle", in the above example,
          use:
                              Default 2

      Default: 0
    Placement: after Data

LabelPlace                                                       OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
      Default: LEFT

Link                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Not valid with calculated type links, such as 'Note' or 'Numbers'.

    Placement: after Data

Spacing                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
The number of pixels between each row.

      Default: 1
@endnode
@node Gad_Slider "Type Slider"
@{fg highlight}Type Slider
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type Slider (
    @{b}Range@{ub} <min> <max>
    @{b}Size@{ub} <width> <height>
    @{b}Direction@{ub} HORIZONTAL|VERTICAL
    LevelPlace LEFT|RIGHT|ABOVE|BELOW
    LevelText <string>
    Link <name>
    Default <#>
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: SLIDER gadgets are equivalent to Integer gadgets, but provide
an alternate method of entering numeric values.

PARAMETERS

@{b}Range@{ub}                                                            REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the range of permitted values for the gadget. <min> must
be less than <max>.

Currently, negative values are not allowed. This may be changed in
a future version.

@{b}Size@{ub}                                                             REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the dimensions of the gadget, in pixels. The value of
<width> and <height> must be within the range of the referenced
window.

@{b}Direction@{ub}                                                        REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the orientation of the gadget.

Default                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This is used to set the default value.

            Default: <min>
          Placement: after Range, after Link

LevelPlace                                                       OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This is used to display a numeric representation of the
current position of the gadget.

            Default: -NONE-

LevelText                                                        OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This text appears after the value display.

            Example:          LevelText "Hz"

             Result:          30 Hz


            Default: ""
          Placement: after LevelPlace

Link                                                             OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Range <min> must be 0 when using links.

          Placement: after Range
@endnode
@node Gad_String "Type String"
@{fg highlight}Type String
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type String (
    @{b}MaxChars@{ub} <#>
    Default <string>
    Width <#>
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: STRING gadgets are used to enter text information (such as
patch names).

PARAMETERS

@{b}MaxChars@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the maximum width, in characters, allowed for entered
          strings.

Default                                                          OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This is used to set the default string. The length of the
default string must be less that MaxChars.

            Default: "" (Null).
          Placement: after MaxChars

Width                                                            OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This is used to set the display width. It may be necessary to
allow entry of a string that is longer than there is space within a
window. By setting the Width parameter to value smaller than the
MaxChars setting, a scrollable string gadget will be created.

          Default: MaxChars
        Placement: after MaxChars
@endnode
@node Link_ARexx "Type ARexx"
@{fg highlight}Type ARexx
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type ARexx (
    Data (
      @{b}@{i}File@{ui}@{ub} <string>
      @{b}@{i}String@{ui}@{ub} <string>
      [...]
    )
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: AREXX link types are used for special circumstances when
additional functionality is necessary beyond what MSE can do with it's
own command set, such as for automating changes to gadgets or calculating
values based on gadget values. Simple ARexx commands can be internal to a
module (String), or larger external scripts can be used (File).

If there is only one data defined that ARexx File/String will be executed
regardless of the value of the gadget that is linked to it. In this case,
it is up to the ARexx File/String to query the calling gadget's value if
necessary.

Alternatively, the number of defined data must match the gadget which has
linked to it. For example, if a 'Slider' type gadget has 'Range 0 4',
there must be 5 data defined here.


PARAMETERS

@{b}@{i}File
String@{ui}@{ub}                                                  OPTIONAL REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
'File' is used to link an external ARexx script to a gadget.

'String' is used to link an ARexx command string to a gadget.
@endnode
@node Link_Envelope "Type Envelope"
@{fg highlight}Type Envelope
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type Envelope (
    @{b}Position@{ub} <left> <top>
    @{b}@{i}Position2@{ui}@{ub} <right> <bottom>
    @{b}@{i}Size@{ui}@{ub} <width> <height>
    @{b}Max@{ub} <x> <y>
    @{b}Data@{ub} (
      <xoffset> <y>
      [...]
    )
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: TEXTS link types allow a gadget to be combined with a
textual representation of the gadget it is linked with. In some cases,
CYCLE gadgets are preferred, as they support a similar function.
However, when there are very many values, the combination of a SLIDER
gadget with a TEXTS link is better.

PARAMETERS

@{b}Position@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the co-ordinates, in pixels, of the upper left hand corner of
the envelope display within the window. The values for <left> and <top>
must be within the range of the window.

@{b}@{i}Size
Position2@{ui}@{ub}                                               OPTIONAL REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
'Size' sets the dimensions of the envelope display, in pixels. The
values of <width> + <left> and <height> + <top> must be within the range
of the window. This is an alternative to 'Position2'. Use one or the
other, but not both.

'Position2' sets the co-ordinates, in pixels, of the lower right hand
corner of the envelope display within the window. The values for <right>
and <bottom> must be within the range of the window and greater than the
<left> and <top> values of 'Position'. This is an alternative to 'Size'.
Use one or the other, but not both.

@{b}Max@{ub}                                                              REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------

@{b}Data@{ub}                                                             REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode
@node Link_Modules "Type Modules"
@{fg highlight}Type Modules
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type Modules (
    @{b}Data@{ub} (
      <name>
      <name>
      [...]
    )
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: MODULES type links are used for linking modules together.
This allows complex device definitions to be broken into smaller 'Part's,
but still appear (visually) as one module. A special selector module
could be defined to allow selection of modules. This link type is
commonly linked with a CYCLE type gadget.
@endnode
@node Link_Note "Type Note"
@{fg highlight}Type Note
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type Note (
    Font <name>
    @{b}Position@{ub} <left> <top>
    @{b}@{i}Position2@{ui}@{ub} <right> <bottom>
    @{b}@{i}Size@{ui}@{ub} <width> <height>
  )

Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: NOTE link types are used to select notes for use with Note
             Ranges, Tunings, etc.

PARAMETERS

@{b}Position@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the offset, in pixels, of the upper left hand corner of
the number display area from the gadget it is linked with. The offsets
for <left> and <top> must be within the range of the referenced window.

@{b}@{i}Size
Position2@{ui}@{ub}                                               OPTIONAL REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
'Size' sets the dimensions of the number display area, in pixels. The
values of <width> + <left> and <height> + <top> must be within the range
of the referenced window. This is an alternative to 'Position2'. Use one
or the other, but not both.

'Position2' sets the offset, in pixels, of the lower right hand corner of
the number display area. The values for <right> and <bottom> must be
within the range of the referenced window. and greater than the <left>
and <top> values of 'Position'. This is an alternative to 'Size'. Use
one or the other, but not both.
@endnode
@node Link_Numbers "Type Numbers"
@{fg highlight}Type Numbers
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type Numbers (
    Font <name>
    @{b}Position@{ub} <left> <top>
    @{b}@{i}Position2@{ui}@{ub} <right> <bottom>
    @{b}@{i}Size@{ui}@{ub} <width> <height>
    @{b}MinValue@{ub} <float>
    @{b}Skip@{ub} <float>
    LevelText <string>
    )
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: NUMBERS link types allow a gadget to be combined with a
numeric representation of the gadget it is linked with. This link type
can provide the same function as a SLIDER gadget but supports additional
features as well.

PARAMETERS

LevelText                                                        OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This text appears after the numeric value display.

            Example:          LevelText "dB"

             Result:          -7.1dB


            Default: ""

@{b}MinValue@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This is the minimum value.

@{b}Position@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the offset, in pixels, of the upper left hand corner of
the number display area from the gadget it is linked with. The offsets
for <left> and <top> must be within the range of the referenced window.

@{b}@{i}Size
Position2@{ui}@{ub}                                               OPTIONAL REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
'Size' sets the dimensions of the number display area, in pixels. The
values of <width> + <left> and <height> + <top> must be within the range
of the referenced window. This is an alternative to 'Position2'. Use one
or the other, but not both.

'Position2' sets the offset, in pixels, of the lower right hand corner of
the number display area. The values for <right> and <bottom> must be
within the range of the referenced window. and greater than the <left>
and <top> values of 'Position'. This is an alternative to 'Size'. Use
one or the other, but not both.

@{b}Skip@{ub}                                                             REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This is the value to increment by.

@endnode
@node Link_Texts "Type Texts"
@{fg highlight}Type Texts
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type Texts (
    Font <name>
    @{b}Position@{ub} <left> <top>
    @{b}@{i}Position2@{ui}@{ub} <right> <bottom>
    @{b}@{i}Size@{ui}@{ub} <width> <height>
    @{b}Data@{ub} (
      <string>
      <string>
      [...]
    )
    DataValues ()
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: TEXTS link types allow a gadget to be combined with a
textual representation of the gadget it is linked with. In some cases,
CYCLE gadgets are preferred, as they support a similar function.
However, when there are very many values, the combination of a SLIDER
gadget with a TEXTS link is better.

PARAMETERS

@{b}Position@{ub}                                                         REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This sets the offset, in pixels, of the upper left hand corner of
the text display area from the gadget it is linked with. The offsets for
<left> and <top> must be within the range of the referenced window.

@{b}@{i}Size
Position2@{ui}@{ub}                                               OPTIONAL REQUIRED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
'Size' sets the dimensions of the text display area, in pixels. The
values of <width> + <left> and <height> + <top> must be within the range
of the referenced window. This is an alternative to 'Position2'. Use one
or the other, but not both.

'Position2' sets the offset, in pixels, of the lower right hand corner of
the text display area. The values for <right> and <bottom> must be within
the range of the referenced window. and greater than the <left> and <top>
values of 'Position'. This is an alternative to 'Size'. Use one or the
other, but not both.

DataValues                                                       OPTIONAL
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This structure is used to define the values for each of the options
included in the 'Data' stucture. If not included, the position within
the list (counting from 0) will be used.

      Example:                DataValues (
                                5 10 15 20
                              )

@endnode
@node Link_Windows "Type Windows"
@{fg highlight}Type Windows
=========================================================================@{fg text}

  Type Windows (
    @{b}Data@{ub} (
      <name>
      <name>
      [...]
    )
  )


Occurance: MULTIPLE

Description: WINDOW type links are used for grouping two or more windows
together, so that only one window is displayed at a time. This is useful
when all the parameters for a device can not be displayed in one window.
This link type is commonly linked with a CYCLE or BUTTON type gadget.
@endnode
